<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="devops-lb-ssl-tls">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>devops-engineer</domain>
    <summary>SSL/TLS termination strategies: termination, re-encryption, passthrough. TLS 1.3 cipher configuration, HSTS, OCSP stapling, and certificate management best practices for 2025-2026.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>ssl</tag>
      <tag>tls</tag>
      <tag>load-balancing</tag>
      <tag>security</tag>
      <tag>certificates</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>infra</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="devops-lb-algorithms"/>
      <ref slug="devops-lb-haproxy"/>
      <ref slug="devops-lb-high-availability"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>SSL/TLS Termination at the Load Balancer</title>

    <summary>The load balancer can terminate TLS (decrypt and forward HTTP to backends), re-encrypt (decrypt and re-encrypt to backends), or pass through (forward encrypted traffic unchanged). Termination is the standard choice; it offloads CPU and enables L7 routing. TLS 1.3 is preferred; TLS 1.2 is the minimum acceptable in 2025-2026.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>TLS termination at the load balancer centralises certificate management, offloads cryptographic CPU cost from backends, and enables the load balancer to inspect HTTP headers for routing decisions. Without termination, each backend must manage its own certificates and handle SSL handshake overhead independently, multiplying operational burden and CPU cost by the number of backend instances.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any public-facing HTTP service — TLS termination at the LB is the standard production pattern.</item>
        <item>Environments that require end-to-end encryption (re-encryption) for compliance (PCI-DSS, HIPAA).</item>
        <item>Services using gRPC or WebSocket over TLS where header inspection is not needed (passthrough).</item>
        <item>Multi-domain services where one LB must serve multiple certificates (SNI-based routing).</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Passthrough mode disables all L7 routing — do not use it if path-based or host-based routing is required.</item>
        <item>Do not terminate TLS on a load balancer that does not hold the private key securely (use HSM or vault-injected secrets).</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="termination-strategies">
      <p>Three termination strategies:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Termination at LB: LB decrypts, sends plain HTTP to backends. Most common. Offloads CPU, enables full L7 inspection. Use when backend network is private and trusted.</item>
        <item>Re-encryption: LB decrypts, re-encrypts to backends using internal certificates. Required for end-to-end encryption compliance. Doubles TLS overhead but ensures traffic is encrypted across the full path.</item>
        <item>TLS Passthrough: LB forwards encrypted traffic without decrypting. Backends must see original TLS. Minimal LB overhead but disables all L7 features (routing, header injection, rate limiting). Use for databases and services that must own the TLS session.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <rules>
      <rule>
        <statement>Configure TLS 1.2 as the minimum version and TLS 1.3 as the preferred version. Disable SSLv3, TLS 1.0, and TLS 1.1 explicitly.</statement>
        <rationale>TLS 1.0 and 1.1 have known vulnerabilities (BEAST, POODLE, FREAK). TLS 1.3 removes legacy cipher suites, requires forward secrecy, and is 1-RTT by default. Clients that require TLS 1.0 are operating software past end-of-life.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Use ECDHE cipher suites with AES-GCM (AES-128-GCM-SHA256, AES-256-GCM-SHA384) and ChaCha20-Poly1305 for TLS 1.3. Disable RSA key exchange and CBC-mode ciphers.</statement>
        <rationale>ECDHE provides perfect forward secrecy — compromising the server's long-term key does not expose past sessions. AES-GCM and ChaCha20-Poly1305 are authenticated encryption algorithms resistant to padding oracle attacks that affected CBC-mode ciphers.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Enable HSTS with max-age of at least 63072000 (2 years) and includeSubDomains. Enable OCSP stapling for faster handshakes.</statement>
        <rationale>HSTS prevents protocol downgrade attacks by telling browsers to reject HTTP connections. OCSP stapling moves certificate revocation checking from the client to the server, eliminating the latency of a client-side OCSP request during the TLS handshake.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Automate certificate renewal with Let's Encrypt ACME protocol or cloud provider certificate managers (AWS ACM, GCP Managed Certs). Never manually manage certificate expiry in production.</statement>
        <rationale>Manual certificate management produces predictable, scheduled outages when certificates expire. ACME automation renews at 60 days before expiry, providing a 30-day window to detect and fix renewal failures before service impact.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </rules>

    <section name="tls-config-examples">
      <example type="good" title="HAProxy modern TLS configuration">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
global
    # TLS 1.3 cipher suites
    ssl-default-bind-ciphersuites TLS_AES_128_GCM_SHA256:TLS_AES_256_GCM_SHA384:TLS_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256
    # TLS 1.2 cipher suites (ECDHE + AES-GCM)
    ssl-default-bind-ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384
    ssl-default-bind-options ssl-min-ver TLSv1.2 no-tls-tickets
    tune.ssl.default-dh-param 2048

frontend https_in
    bind *:443 ssl crt /etc/haproxy/certs/ alpn h2,http/1.1
    # HSTS 2 years + subdomains + preload
    http-response set-header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=63072000; includeSubDomains; preload"
    http-response set-header X-Content-Type-Options nosniff
    http-response set-header X-Frame-Options DENY

# HTTP to HTTPS redirect
frontend http_redirect
    bind *:80
    http-request redirect scheme https code 301 unless { ssl_fc }
]]></code>
        <note>ssl-min-ver TLSv1.2 disables TLS 1.0 and 1.1. alpn h2,http/1.1 enables HTTP/2. no-tls-tickets disables TLS session tickets (forward secrecy for resumed sessions).</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Nginx modern TLS configuration">
        <code lang="nginx"><![CDATA[
server {
    listen 443 ssl http2;
    server_name example.com;

    ssl_certificate /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.crt;
    ssl_certificate_key /etc/nginx/ssl/example.com.key;
    ssl_session_timeout 1d;
    ssl_session_cache shared:SSL:50m;
    ssl_session_tickets off;

    # TLS 1.2 + 1.3 only
    ssl_protocols TLSv1.2 TLSv1.3;
    ssl_ciphers ECDHE-ECDSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-RSA-AES128-GCM-SHA256:ECDHE-ECDSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384:ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384;
    ssl_prefer_server_ciphers off;

    # HSTS
    add_header Strict-Transport-Security "max-age=63072000" always;
}

server {
    listen 80;
    server_name example.com;
    return 301 https://$server_name$request_uri;
}
]]></code>
        <note>ssl_prefer_server_ciphers off allows TLS 1.3 to use client-preferred ciphers (all TLS 1.3 suites are secure). ssl_session_tickets off disables session ticket resumption for better forward secrecy.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="Weak TLS configuration with legacy protocols">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
# DO NOT use:
ssl_protocols SSLv3 TLSv1 TLSv1.1 TLSv1.2;
ssl_ciphers ALL:!ADH:!EXPORT:!LOW:+HIGH:+MEDIUM;
]]></code>
        <note>SSLv3 and TLS 1.0/1.1 are vulnerable. The cipher string HIGH:MEDIUM includes CBC-mode ciphers vulnerable to BEAST and Lucky 13 attacks. Use explicit ECDHE+AESGCM lists instead.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>Disable SSLv3, TLS 1.0, TLS 1.1 — enable TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3 only.</check>
      <check>Use ECDHE cipher suites with AES-GCM for TLS 1.2; allow all TLS 1.3 defaults.</check>
      <check>Enable perfect forward secrecy (ECDHE key exchange).</check>
      <check>Set DH parameter to 2048+ bits (tune.ssl.default-dh-param in HAProxy).</check>
      <check>Enable HSTS with max-age >= 63072000.</check>
      <check>Enable OCSP stapling.</check>
      <check>Automate certificate renewal (Let's Encrypt ACME, AWS ACM, GCP Managed Certs).</check>
      <check>Store private keys in HSM or secrets vault — never in plaintext files with loose permissions.</check>
      <check>Test with SSL Labs and target A+ rating.</check>
      <check>Verify HTTP to HTTPS redirect returns 301.</check>
    </checklist>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Using the default Nginx ssl_ciphers or HAProxy cipher list without explicitly disabling legacy ciphers.</description>
      <reason>Default cipher lists historically include RC4, 3DES, and CBC-mode ciphers for backward compatibility. Attackers can force downgrade to these weak ciphers if the client supports them. Always specify an explicit allowlist.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Storing TLS private keys as unencrypted PEM files owned by the web server user with world-readable permissions.</description>
      <reason>Any process running as that user can read the private key and decrypt past or future sessions. Use filesystem permissions (mode 600, root ownership) and ideally inject keys from a secrets manager at runtime.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://livingdevops.com/devops/ssl-termination-complete-guide-2025/"/>
      <link href="https://ssl-config.mozilla.org/"/>
      <link href="https://www.ssllabs.com/ssltest/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
